      "question": "If $\\sin(A + B) = 1$ and $\\cos(A - B) = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}$, where $0^\\circ < A + B \\le 90^\\circ$ and $A > B$, find the values of $A$ and $B$.",
      "answer": "A = 60^\\circ, B = 30^\\circ",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Use the trigonometric table values for $\\sin$ and $\\cos$.",
          "Set up the system of linear equations based on the given angles.",
          "Solve for $A$ and $B$ by adding and subtracting the equations."
        ],
        "derivation": "\\sin(A+B) = 1 \\implies A+B = 90^\\circ \\quad (1) \\\\ \\cos(A-B) = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\implies A-B = 30^\\circ \\quad (2) \\\\ (1)+(2): 2A = 120^\\circ \\implies A = 60^\\circ \\\\ (1)-(2): 2B = 60^\\circ \\implies B = 30^\\circ"
      },
