    {
      "question": "If $7 \\sin^2 \\theta + 3 \\cos^2 \\theta = 4$, show that $\\tan \\theta = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}$.",
      "answer": "\\tan \\theta = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Express $\\cos^2 \\theta$ as $1 - \\sin^2 \\theta$ using the identity $\\sin^2 \\theta + \\cos^2 \\theta = 1$.",
          "Solve the resulting linear equation for $\\sin^2 \\theta$.",
          "Calculate $\\tan \\theta$ using the values of $\\sin \\theta$ and $\\cos \\theta$."
        ],
        "derivation": "7 \\sin^2 \\theta + 3(1 - \\sin^2 \\theta) = 4 \\\\ 7 \\sin^2 \\theta + 3 - 3 \\sin^2 \\theta = 4 \\\\ 4 \\sin^2 \\theta = 1 \\implies \\sin^2 \\theta = \\frac{1}{4} \\implies \\sin \\theta = \\frac{1}{2} \\\\ \\cos^2 \\theta = 1 - \\frac{1}{4} = \\frac{3}{4} \\implies \\cos \\theta = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\\\ \\tan \\theta = \\frac{\\sin \\theta}{\\cos \\theta} = \\frac{1/2}{\\sqrt{3}/2} = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}"
      },
